  "prompt": "What IDE do you use for C/C++?",
  "response": "There are several popular integrated development environments (IDEs) that developers commonly use for C/C++ programming. Some of the most well-regarded options include:\n\n1. **Visual Studio**: Developed by Microsoft, Visual Studio is a powerful IDE with robust tooling for C++ development. It features intelliSense (smart code completion), debugging tools, code navigation, and numerous extensions.\n\n2. **CLion**: Developed by JetBrains, CLion offers a smart and feature-rich environment for C and C++ development. It provides advanced code analysis, refactoring tools, and seamless integration with CMake.\n\n3. **Eclipse CDT (C/C++ Development Tooling)**: Eclipse is a well-known open-source IDE with a strong plugin ecosystem. The CDT plugin adds powerful C/C++ development capabilities, including code completion, debugging, and project management.\n\n4. **Code::Blocks**: This is an open-source, cross-platform IDE specifically designed for C/C++. It offers a customizable interface, plugin support, and is highly regarded for its simplicity and portability.\n\n5. **Dev-C++**: An older, yet still widely used IDE for C/C++. It is lightweight and simple, making it suitable for beginners.\n\n6. **Xcode**: If you're on a macOS system, Xcode is an excellent choice for C/C++ and other programming languages. It offers all-in-one development tools, including a powerful debugger, interface builder, and code completion.\n\n7. **Qt Creator**: Primarily aimed at developing with the Qt framework, Qt Creator nevertheless provides full-featured support for standard C++ development.\n\n8. **NetBeans**: Known more for Java development, NetBeans also supports C/C++ with additional plugins. It features a rich set of tools for code editing, project management, and debugging.\n\nChoosing the right IDE often depends on your specific requirements, such as platform, integrations, and personal preferences in terms of interface and features.",
